  <h1>Cybersecurity Newsfeed</h1>
  <h2>📅 26/02/26</h2>

  <h2>🛡️ Vulnerabilities</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Critical Zyxel Router Flaw (CVE-2025-13942)</strong>: Zyxel released patches for a critical RCE vulnerability (CVSS 9.8) in the UPnP function of various 4G LTE/5G NR, DSL, and Fiber ONT models. Unauthenticated attackers can send crafted SOAP requests to execute arbitrary OS commands. While WAN access is disabled by default, enabled UPnP services pose a significant risk. Additional fixes address post-auth injection and DoS flaws. <a href="https://securityaffairs.com/188501/security/critical-zyxel-router-flaw-exposed-devices-to-remote-attacks.html" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>Cisco Catalyst SD-WAN Exploited in the Wild</strong>: CISA added two Cisco vulnerabilities to its KEV catalog following active exploitation by threat actor UAT-8616 since 2023. CVE-2026-20127 (CVSS 10.0) allows unauthenticated administrative access to SD-WAN Controllers. Attackers then downgrade software to exploit CVE-2022-20775 for root privilege escalation. Federal agencies must patch by Feb 27, 2026. <a href="https://www.cisa.gov/news-events/alerts/2026/02/25/cisa-adds-two-known-exploited-vulnerabilities-catalog" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>Soliton FileZen Command Injection (CVE-2026-25108)</strong>: CISA warns of active exploitation against FileZen secure file transfer appliances. This OS command injection flaw (CVSS 8.7) allows low-privileged authenticated attackers to execute arbitrary commands, provided the Antivirus Check Option is enabled. Users are urged to upgrade to v5.0.11+ and reset all user passwords. <a href="https://www.helpnetsecurity.com/2026/02/25/cve-2026-25108-filezen-vulnerability-exploited/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>🎯 Adversaries</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Google Disrupts Chinese UNC2814 Campaign</strong>: Google Threat Intelligence disrupted a global espionage campaign targeting 53 organizations in 42 countries. The group used a C-based backdoor called "Gridtide," which abused the Google Sheets API for C2 communication to hide in plain sight. Targeting focused on telecoms and government PII, likely for surveillance of persons of interest. <a href="https://www.theregister.com/2026/02/25/google_and_friends_disrupt_unc2814/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>Oblivion Android RAT Bypasses Security Layers</strong>: Researchers identified "Oblivion," a sophisticated Android RAT sold for $300/month. Distributed via fake system updates, it abuses Accessibility Services to bypass protections on Samsung and Xiaomi devices. It features a "hidden mode" that displays fake animations while attackers stream the screen, log keys, and steal 2FA codes. <a href="https://hackread.com/android-malware-oblivion-fake-updates-hijack-phones/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>📈 Trends</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Malicious Next.js Repos Target Developers</strong>: Microsoft Defender uncovered a campaign by North Korean-linked actors targeting developers with fake job-themed technical assessments. Malicious Next.js repositories trigger RCE when a dev opens the project in VS Code or starts a local server, leading to data exfiltration and persistent C2 access. <a href="https://www.bleepingcomputer.com/news/security/fake-nextjs-job-interview-tests-backdoor-developers-devices/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>Stripe.net Typosquatting on NuGet</strong>: A malicious package named "StripeApi.Net" mimicked the official Stripe library to steal API tokens and machine identifiers. The package artificially inflated its download count to 180,000 to gain trust. Though removed in mid-February, it highlights a shift in supply chain attacks toward financial service integrations. <a href="https://www.infosecurity-magazine.com/news/malicious-nuget-package-stripe-devs/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>
  </ul>

  <h2>📚 Others</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>RAMP Forum Seizure Fractures Ecosystem</strong>: Following the FBI's seizure of the RAMP ransomware forum on Jan 28, 2026, the ecosystem has fragmented. Rapid7 notes threat actors are migrating to gated platforms like T1erOne and open forums like Rehub. This shift complicates law enforcement visibility and forces defenders to monitor smaller, diverse clusters. <a href="https://www.darkreading.com/threat-intelligence/ramp-forum-seizure-fractures-ransomware-ecosystem" target="_blank">More info</a></li>

    <li><strong>US Sanctions Exploit Broker Operation Zero</strong>: The Treasury sanctioned Sergey Zelenyuk and his firm, Operation Zero, for trafficking stolen government cyber tools. The action follows the sentencing of a former L3Harris executive who sold zero-day exploits to the firm for $1.3M in crypto. These are the first sanctions issued under the Protecting American Intellectual Property Act. <a href="https://hackread.com/us-sanctions-russian-exploit-broker-us-cyber-tools/" target="_blank">More info</a></li>
  </ul>

